The paper deals with a conjecture related to the degree of GF(2) polynomials and their Fourier sparsity, which suggests that certain conditions on the highest degree monomials of a polynomial can determine its Fourier sparsity regardless of the lower degree monomials. This suggests a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC), information theory (cs.IT), data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), and computational geometry (cs.CG).
